{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti** explicitly enumerates the body's senses as eleven in total: the five organs of cognition (ear, skin, eyes, tongue, and nose); the five organs of action (anus, generative organ, hands, feet, and speech); and the mind as the eleventh.[^1]\n\n**San Hyan Tattvajnana** describes the five senses of perception (eye, ear, nose, tongue, and skin, or *pañcendriya*) and the five senses of action (speech, hands, feet, organ of generation, and organ of excretion, or *pañcakarmendriya*), totaling ten senses plus the *manas* as the eleventh.[^2] It further details the corresponding subtle elements (*tanmātras*): sound (*śabdatanmātra*), touch (*sparśatanmātra*), form (*rūpatanmātra*), taste (*rasatanmātra*), and smell (*gandhatanmātra*).\n\n**Kalpabuddha** identifies the five senses (*pañcendriya*) within the body as: eyes (*cakṣus*), ears (*śrotra*), nose (*ghrāṇa*), mouth (*jihvā*), and liver/heart (*hṛdaya*), associating each with a deity of the Pañcatathāgata.[^3]\n\n**Gaṇapatitattva** refers to the emergence of fifteen senses from the divine Selves (*ātman*s) and discusses restraining or withdrawing the senses (*indriya*) in yogic practice, but does not list them explicitly by name.[^4]\n\nSeveral other works mention the senses (*indriya*) metaphorically (e.g., as objects of restraint, enemies, or sources of attachment) but lack explicit descriptions of the body's senses.[^5] No works in Western or poetic genres (e.g., Cynewulf, Ghalib, or Comte) cover this topic.\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 2*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-118055).\n[^2]: San Hyan Tattvajnana, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-tattvajnana-1f29bd/01/translation/#p-d681ce).\n[^3]: Kalpabuddha, *Chapter 6*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-kalpabuddha-d760dc/06/translation/#p-c8567e).\n[^4]: Gaṇapatitattva, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-858826).\n[^5]: E.g., Parāśara Smṛti, *Chapter 8*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/08/translation/#p-ab1289); Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana, *Chapter 1*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-39472d).",
